{"id":14881127,"mediaExerciseId":"ffa74129-7eac-4d51-93be-87e47f6b462a","exerciseName":"8","chapterName":"8","chapterTitle":"Stock Valuation","groupId":612321,"groupTitle":"Questions and Problems","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":266,"solutions":[{"id":6050129,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"\nIn this problem, we have to find out the **required return**. The formula we will use for the calculation is the constant growth model.\n\n$$\\begin{align}\nP_0&=\\frac{D_1}{R-g}\n\\end{align}$$\n\nwhere,\n$$\\begin{align}\nR&=\\frac{D_1}{P_0}+g\n\\end{align}$$\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"We have the following information.\n\n* The dividend $D_1$ is equal to $\\$3.40$\n\n* The currently sells $P_0$ is equal to  $\\$91$\n\n* Because the preferred stock pays a constant dividend, the dividend growth rate should be assumed to be zero.\n\n\nNow, let's do the calculation according to the formula which we denote with $(2)$.\n\n\n$$\\begin{align*}\nR&=\\frac{D_1}{P_0}+g\\\\[12pt]\n&=\\frac{\\$3.40}{\\$91}+0\\\\[12pt]\n&=0.0373\\\\[7pt]\n&=3.73\\%.\n\\end{align*}$$\n\nTherefore, we can conclude that the required return is $R=3.73\\%.$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"$\\boxed{3.73\\%.}$","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":true,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"b00acf4c-78e1-4811-b6f6-867157a97d7c","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3